elements.Text: Safety of diagnostic flexible bronchoscopy in patients with echocardiographic evidence of pulmonary hypertension
Tsukasa Ishiwata, Mitsuhiro Abe, Hajime Kasai, Jun Ikari, Naoko Kawata, Jiro Terada, Seiichiro Sakao, Yuji Tada, Nobuhiro Tanabe, Koichiro Tatsumi
Department of Respirology, Graduate School of Medicine, Chiba University, 1-8-1, Inohana, Chuo-ku, Chiba 260-8670, Japan

Background: The presence of pulmonary hypertension (PH) and treatment with anticoagulant agents could potentially increase the risk for bleeding/hemodynamic complications associated with bronchoscopic procedures. The aim of this study was to assess the safety of diagnostic flexible bronchoscopy (FB) in patients with PH.

Methods: A retrospective review of clinical records of patients with echocardiographic evidence of PH (right ventricular systolic pressure [RVSP] 4 40 mm Hg) who underwent diagnostic FB between 2004 and 2016 at a single facility in Japan was conducted. Patients with no clinical evidence suggestive of PH who underwent FB during the same period were enrolled as a pairwise-matched control group; factors used in matching included age, sex, and performed procedures.

Results: Overall, there were 45 patients in the PH group and 90 patients in the control group. Six (13%) patients in the PH group had severe PH (RVSP 4 61 mm Hg). Forceps biopsies and transbronchial needle aspirations were performed in 62% and 13% of patients, respectively, in the PH group, and 58% and 13% of patients, respectively, in the control group. The total incidence of bleeding during FB was not significantly different between the two groups (18% versus 16%; p ¼ 0.742). Vital signs recorded 2 h after FB were also not significantly different between the two groups. There were no episodes of cardiac arrhythmias or deaths associated with the FB procedures.
Conclusions: The data suggest that diagnostic FB procedures can be performed safely in patients with echocardiographic evidence of PH.

Flexible bronchoscopy (FB) is a clinical tool indispensable for endobronchial assessments, including identification of causative microorganisms of pulmonary infiltrates, and diagnosis of lung masses or lymphadenopathy of unknown etiology. The complications of FB and related procedures include bleeding, hypoxemia, pneumothorax, cardiac dysrhythmias, bronchospasm, fever, and infection. A nationwide survey performed in Japan revealed that the incidence of complications associated with diagnostic bronchoscopic procedures ranged from 0.17% to 1.93%, depending on the type of intervention (<>)[1]. The survey revealed an extremely low rate of severe complications, including a mortality rate of 0.004%. Therefore, FB is considered to be a safe procedure.

Pulmonary hypertension (PH) is a relatively rare disease defined by elevated pulmonary arterial pressure. In Japan, according to the Intractable Diseases Information Center, the estimated prevalences of pulmonary arterial hypertension and chronic thromboembolic PH were 23.4 and 20.0 per 100,000 population in 2014 (<>)[2].

Prolonged PH leads to right ventricular dysfunction because of the sustained increase in afterload to the right ventricle. In the case of added stresses, such as surgical intervention(s), patients with PH may fail to accommodate the needed changes in right ventricular preload or afterload, at least in part due to alterations of the autonomic nervous system (<>)[3]. As a result, PH patients have a higher risk for complications, such as cardiac dysrhythmias and hemody-namic fluctuations, during surgery (<>)[4].

Several reports have suggested that bronchoscopic procedures can also be performed safely in patients with PH (<>)[5,(<>)6]. However, patients with severe PH often receive anticoagulant therapy and/or prostaglandin I2, also known as prostacyclin (<>)[7]. None of the previous reports addressing the safety of FB in PH patients have clearly reported the percentage of patients receiving antithrombotic agents. The objective of the present study, conducted at a single facility in Japan with a specialized PH center, was to assess the safety of bronchoscopic interventions in a population of PH patients, including those receiving antithrombotic agents.

This study was a retrospective review of data from a prospectively maintained database and medical records at Chiba University Hospital (Chiba, Japan). The study protocol was approved by the Institutional Review Board (Chiba #2455, September 1, 2016). Written informed consent for FB was obtained from all participants. All procedures performed in studies involving human participants were in accordance with the ethical standards of the institution, and with the 1964 Helsinki Declaration and its later amendments, or comparable ethical standards.

Patients who underwent diagnostic FB between April 2004 and December 2016, for whom echocardiographic data obtained within three months of (before or after) FB were available, were enrolled. The study included a PH group, consisting of patients who were diagnosed with PH, defined as a right ventricular systolic pressure (RVSP) estimated by Doppler echocardiogra-phy 4 40 mm Hg (PH group), and a control group consisting of pairwise-matched (1:2) patients who underwent FB during the same period but exhibited no clinical evidence suggestive of PH. Factors used for matching included age, sex, and types of procedures performed. If therewas more than onematched case, a control case was selected from among the matched cases using the random sampling function in Excel software (Microsoft Corporation, Redmond, WA, USA). At the authors’ institution, FB is avoided in patients who have severe dyspnea despite receiving supplemental oxygen, refractory hypotension (systolic blood pressure o 80 mm Hg), uncontrolled ventricular arrhythmias, or heart failure requiring catecholamine support.

The FB procedures included endobronchial biopsy (EBB), transbronchial biopsy (TBB), transbronchial needle aspiration (TBNA, including endobronchial ultrasound-guided TBNA), bronchoalveolar lavage (BAL), bronchial brushing, and endo-bronchial observation. In some of the patients undergoing TBB, a guide sheath (GS) was used as a guide and a cover for the TBB forceps. For each patient, the following clinical information was extracted from the medical records: age; sex; race; presence of comorbidities, such as congestive heart failure, obstructive airway impairment, chronic kidney disease, chronic liver disease, and malignancy; echocardio-graphic data; laboratory parameters measured immediately before FB; use of antithrombotic agents; indications for FB; the FB procedures performed; complications associated with the FB interventions; and vital signs recorded before and 2 h after FB.

In the present study, bleeding was defined as follows: mild (need for continuous suctioning with a bronchoscope); moderate (need for wedging of the bronchoscope into the bronchus); and severe (need for additional interventions, such as placement of a bronchus blocker or admission to a critical care unit). Hypoxemia was defined as the need for supplemental oxygen via an oxygen mask or the need for tracheal intubation. Hypotension was defined as a systolic blood pressure o 80 mm Hg or need for administration of vasopressor agents. Arrhythmias were defined as the appearance of new cardiac dysrhythmias.

All patients underwent FB with continuous monitoring using standard procedures, including electrocardiography, pulse oximetry, and noninvasive blood pressure monitoring. Supplemental oxygen at a flow rate of 2 L/min was administered via a nasal cannula. All procedures were performed under conscious sedation. Sedation was achieved using midazolam

and/or pethidine hydrochloride. The sedative agents were administered intravenously, as needed, for conscious sedation by the attending pulmonologists. Topical anesthesia was administered using 1% lidocaine.

At the authors’ institution, antithrombotic agents are routinely withdrawn before FB interventions. However, in patients with high embolic risk after discontinuation of anticoagulant medications, such as warfarin, heparin is routinely administered as a substitute for oral anticoagulation. Continuous heparin infusion is stopped 4 h before FB and resumed immediately after completion of FB.

Descriptive data are expressed as number (percentage), and continuous data as mean and standard deviation for normally distributed data. For statistical comparisons, descriptive data were compared using the chi-squared test or Fisher's exact test. The continuous data were compared using the t-test for normally distributed data, and the Mann-Whitney test for non-normally distributed data. All p values were two-sided and statistical significance was set at p o 0.05. All analyses and data interpretation were performed using SAS version 9.4 (SAS Institute Inc., Cary, NC, USA).

In this study, therewere45patientswithPHdiagnosed on the basis of echocardiographic evidence in the PH group, and 90 patients with no clinical evidence suggestive of PH in the control group. Characteristics of patients in both groups are summarized in (<>)Table 1. The mean age was 69.0 7 13.8 years in the PH group versus (vs.) 69.5 7 13.5 years in the control group. The majority of patients were Japanese (the control group included one Chinese and one Thai patient). The prevalence of comorbidities, including congestive heart failure (22% vs. 2%; p o 0.001), obstructive airway impairment (20% vs. 7%; p ¼ 0.038) and chronic liver disease (11% vs. 2%; p ¼ 0.041), was higher in the PH group. The prothrombin time (12.6 7 3.6 vs. 10.7 7 0.9 s; p o 0.001) and activated partial thromboplastin time (35.6 7 8.7 vs. 31.2 7 5.3 s; p ¼ 0.003) before FB were significantly more prolonged in the PH group. PH in the PH group was classified according to the clinical classification of PH (Nice, 2013), as follows: group 1 (pulmonary arterial hypertension, 49%); group 2 (due to left heart disease, 22%); group 3 (due to lung disease and/or hypoxemia, 18%); or group 4 (chronic thromboembolic PH, 11%). There were no patients in group 5 PH (with unclear multifactorial mechanisms). The mean serum level of brain natriuretic peptide in the PH group was 69.8 pg/mL (normal, r18.4 pg/mL). The percentage of patients receiving antithrombotic agents was higher in the PH group (44% vs. 20%; p ¼ 0.003). None of the patients included in the study required mechanical ventilation during/after FB. There were no episodes of cardiac arrhythmias or deaths associated with the FB procedures in this study. With regard to late-phase complications developing within 2 weeks after FB, one patient in the PH group developed pneumonia and 1 in the control group developed exacerbation of interstitial lung disease. Fifteen patients in the PH group underwent right heart catheterization within 1 month of Doppler echocardiography. In the present study, we demonstrated that the incidence of complications associated with FB interventions under conscious sedation in patients with echocardiographic evidence of PH was not significantly higher than that in the control group. In particular, the rate of bleeding events associated with bronchoscopic interventions, such as EBB, TBB, TBNA, BAL and bronchial brushing, was quite similar between the two groups. Moreover, PH patients exhibited no increase in the risk for hemodynamic complications associated with FB procedures.

We demonstrated that FB procedures were not associated with an increased risk for bleeding in patients with PH. In general, major complications associated with FB procedures are rare (<>)[1,(<>)8,(<>)9]. On the other hand, it is believed that patients with PH may be at an increased risk for bleeding events. For example, a previous study reported that PH causes dilatation of the submucosal bronchial veins and their plexuses (<>)[10], which could potentially increase the risk for bleeding after EBB/TBB procedures. However, to date, no clear evidence of an increased risk for bleeding associated with bronchoscopic interventions has been reported in patients with PH. In our study population, the percentage of patients receiving antith-rombotic agents before FB was higher in the PH group. According to the protocol at our institution, antithrombotic agents are routinely withdrawn before FB interventions, and heparin is administered as a substitute for oral anticoagulant therapy in patients with a high embolic risk after discontinuation of oral anticoagulation with agents such as warfarin or non-vitamin K antagonists. In this study, 18% of PH patients received continuous infusion of heparin until immediately before the FB. However, the incidence of bleeding events during FB procedures in the PH group was similar to that in the control group. Furthermore, our subgroup analysis revealed that there were no bleeding events in the 3 patients with severe PH (RVSP 4 61 mm Hg) who underwent EBB/TBB. In a previous prospective study that examined the risk for bleeding in patients with interstitial lung disease and PH undergoing transbronchial lung biopsy, no significant

difference was observed in the rate of bleeding events (blood loss 410 mL) between the PH group and the control group (4.5% vs. 3.6%) (<>)[5]. In addition, one retrospective study reported the absence of any differences in the incidence of bleeding events between 107 patients with PH and a control group, and concluded that FB procedures were safe to perform in patients with PH (<>)[11], although none of the patients in the PH group were receiving anticoagulant agents. One reason for the low rate of bleeding complications in the PH group, even though PH is associated with a bleeding risk, could be the use of GS while performing TBB. Consistent with previous reports, the use of a GS during TBB is useful for stopping bleeding, because the GS is placed immediately in front of the target in the lung and acts to shield the biopsied bronchus (<>)[12,(<>)13].

In addition, the present study also demonstrated that patients with PH did not have an increased risk of complications such as hypoxemia, hypotension, or cardiac dysrhyth-mias, compared with the control group. A previous report indicated that the risk for hemodynamic complications after non-cardiac surgery was elevated in patients with PH (<>)[14] and, according to yet another report, the risk of adverse hemodynamic events was particularly high in patients with severe PH (<>)[15]. However, in our study, none of the patients with PH developed hypotension or cardiac dysrhythmias as complications of FB, although no invasive hemodynamic monitoring was performed. Several previous reports may lend support to our results. In a retrospective study involving 45 patients with PH, there were no cases of refractory hypotension or hemodynamic instability associated with FB procedures (<>)[6]. In a study involving 40 patients with PH complicating chronic obstructive lung disease (i.e., patients with group 3 PH according to the clinical classification of PH), hemodynamic parameters, including heart rate and blood pressure recorded after the FB procedures, were similar between the PH group and control group (<>)[16].

There were several limitations to the present study. First, there was a selection bias because as a rule, we avoid FB interventions in PH patients with unstable respiratory status or extremely severe heart failure at our institution. Furthermore, there were only a small number of patients with severe PH. Therefore, our results should be interpreted with caution. There is a possibility that this result cannot be applied to all PH patients. Second, we could not fully evaluate the adequacy of sampling. Therefore, there could have been differences among cases in how aggressively the operators performed the diagnostic FB procedures/observations. It is possible that attempts at obtaining larger/more adequate samples may be associated with an increased risk for complications in patients with PH, although the number of biopsies did not differ significantly between the two groups. Third, the diagnosis of PH in this study was made based on the findings of Doppler echocardiography, even though the gold standard method for diagnosing PH is right heart catheterization. However, use of echocardiography for the diagnosis of PH has been well validated (<>)[17,(<>)18]. Fourth, no echocardiographic assessments were conducted in patients in the control group - it is possible that the control group also included patients with PH. However, as experts specialized in the diagnosis/management of PH, we included only patients who exhibited no symptoms/signs suggestive of PH according to the clinical medical records used in this study.

The present study demonstrated that FB procedures performed under conscious sedation, including EBB, TBB, TBNA, BAL, and bronchial brushing, can be executed safely in patients with echocardiographic evidence of PH. Moreover, the risk for complications, including bleeding, hypoxemia, hypotension, and cardiac dysrhythmias, is not increased in this patient population compared with that in patients without PH. Nevertheless, we still recommend caution while performing FB in patients with severe PH because the safety data for this patient subgroup are limited.
